\begin_layout Exercise
Find the Marshallian demand from the following utility functions: (i) (Leontief)
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2})=min\{\alpha_{1}x_{1},\alpha_{2}x_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 and (ii) (linear) 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2})=x_{1}+x_{2}$
\end_inset

, subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}x_{1}+p_{2}x_{2}=w$
\end_inset

 for strictly positive prices and positive wealth.
 (Hint: you cannot use the KKT conditions for (i) because the Leontief function
 is non-differentiable).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Consider the following problem, the consumer has a continuous utility function
 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined over 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

, his budget constraint is given by a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $b:X\times\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}\mapsto\mathbb{R}_{++}^{L}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b(x,p)\leq w$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is a positive amount of wealth.
 (i) Show that the Utility Maximization Problem with the non-linear budget
 constraint defined before has a solution.
 (ii) Describe sufficient conditions over the function 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 (i.e., convexity/concavity with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

) and over 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 such that the solution is unique.
 (iii) What is the Slutsky matrix in this case (Hint: Recall that a Slutsky
 demand is 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{slutsky}(p,q)=x(p,p'q)$
\end_inset

 in the linear budget constraint case when 
\begin_inset Formula $b(x,p)=p'x$
\end_inset

, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $b(x,p)=w$
\end_inset

 in this part).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
(i) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 be rational preferences that are locally non-satiated.
 Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $u:X\mapsto\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 represents this 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 then the UMP problem 
\begin_inset Formula $max_{x\geq0}u(x)$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p'x\leq w$
\end_inset

 has as a solution a Marshallian demand 
\begin_inset Formula $x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 that satisfies Walras' law.
 (ii) Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 are monotone instead of locally non-satiated the Marshallian demand that
 solves the UMP problem satisfies Walras' law.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
Consider the Cobb-Douglas case 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x_{1},x_{2})=x_{1}^{\alpha}x_{2}^{1-\alpha}$
\end_inset

 for the UMP problem with linear constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}x_{1}+p_{2}x_{2}=w$
\end_inset

.
 (i) Solve the UMP, (ii) solve the associated EMP.
 (iii) Compute the indirect utility, the expenditure function.
 (iv) Verify Roy's Identity and Sheppard's lemma.
 (v) Verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p,v(p,w))=x(p,w)$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $w=e(p,v(p,w))$
\end_inset

.
 (vi) Verify the Slutsky Equation.
 
\end_layout

